{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}
{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}
'''Neil R. MacCallum''' (15 May 1954 &ndash; 9 November 2002) was a [[Scottish nationalist]] political activist and poet.

Born in [[Edinburgh]], MacCallum studied at Firrhill High School and [[Napier College]] before working for the [[Lothian Health Board]].<ref name="scotsman" />  In this role, he joined the [[NALGO]] trade union and served for a while as a [[shop steward]].<ref>Linda Anderson, Bob Bright and Jon Kimber, ''General Election Guide 1983'', p.225 (BBC Data)</ref>  He joined the [[Scottish National Party]] (SNP) while young, and attended the 1972 [[Plaid Cymru]] conference with a group of friends from the SNP, drawing attention by playing the [[bagpipes]] at the event.<ref name="independent">Peter D. Wright, "[http://scotsindependent.scot/oldsitearchive/scotind/features/maccallum_neil.htm Neil R MacCallum]", ''[[Scots Independent]]''</ref>

MacCallum was elected to [[Edinburgh City Council]] in 1977, representing Wester Hailes.  He lost his seat in 1980, but was elected as Assistant National Secretary of the SNP, then National Secretary the following year.<ref name="scotsman">"[http://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/neil-maccallum-1-629520 Neil MacCallum]", ''[[The Scotsman]]'', 21 November 2002</ref>  While Secretary, he chaired the SNP Commission of Inquiry into the party's structures, and it was he who convinced party leader [[Gordon Wilson (Scottish politician)|Gordon Wilson]] to include [[Alex Salmond]] as a member.<ref>David Torrance, ''Salmond: Against The Odds''</ref>  He also stood as a candidate in the [[United Kingdom general election, 1983|1983 general election]] in [[Edinburgh South (UK Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh South]], taking fourth place with 5.0% of the vote.<ref>"[http://www.politicsresources.net/area/uk/ge83/i08.htm  UK General Election results June 1983]", ''Richard Kimber's Political Science Resources''</ref>  He stood down in 1986, following ill health, and was succeeded by his assistant, [[John Swinney]].<ref name="independent" />

MacCallum also wrote poetry in [[Scots language|Lowland Scots]], his work first appearing in "Out of Charity" in 1973, and from the late 1980s, he published compilations of other poetry in the language.  In the 1990s, he became active in the [[Scots Language Society]] and served on the board of the [[Scottish Poetry Library]], and acted as arts correspondent for the ''[[Scots Independent]]'' newspaper.<ref name="scotsman" />

In later life, MacCallum suffered with depression and problematic drinking, and went missing on several occasions.  In November 2002, he fell into the [[Union Canal (Scotland)|Union Canal]] and died later the same day from [[hypothermia]].<ref name="scotsman" />

