[[Category:Chinese philosophy]] [[Category:Philosophical concepts]] [[Category:Emotion]] [[Category:Philosophy of mind]] [[Category:Neo-Confucianism]] [[Category:Confucianism]]

[[File:The London Institution, Moorfields, London; the facade and a Wellcome V0013228.jpg|thumb|The London Institution, Moorfields, London, 1819 (attributed)]] [[File:Spa Road railway station 1836.jpg|thumb|[[Spa Road railway station]], [[Bermondsey]], 1836]]
'''Robert Blemmell{{refn|group=nb|Sometimes (erroneously?) spelled as ''Blemmel'' or ''Bremmell'' in sources.}} Schnebbelie''' (16 September 1781<ref name="Harleian">{{cite book|title=The Publications of the Harleian Society: Registers, Volume 2; Volume 4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2SjvAAAAMAAJ|year=1878|publisher=[[Harleian Society|The Harleian Society]]|page=36}}</ref> – 1847<ref name="MoL">{{cite web|url=http://www.museumoflondonprints.com/image/1002871/robert-b-schnebbelie-spa-road-temporary-terminus-london-greenwich-railway-1836|title=Spa Road Temporary Terminus, London & Greenwich Railway, 1836|publisher=Museum of London|accessdate=10 December 2016}}</ref>{{refn|group=nb|Schnebbelie's year of death is stated by many sources to have been 1849, based on John Bowyer Nichols's statement that it happened "about the year 1849";<ref name="Nichols" /> however, the records of [[Metropolitan Borough of St Pancras|St Pancras parish]] state that he died in 1847,<ref name="FMP-death">[http://search.findmypast.co.uk/record?id=bmd%2fd%2f1847%2f2%2faz%2f000710%2f146 St Pancras, London, parish death records]</ref> which other sources verify, so Nichols's later date is clearly mistaken.}}) was an English painter and illustrator. He produced numerous paintings and drawings of [[London]]'s topography during the first half of the 19th century.<ref name="Gallery1951">{{cite book|title=London Pictures: A Selection of Paintings from the Permanent Collection of the Corporation of London|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9gNNAAAAYAAJ|year=1951|publisher=[[Guildhall Art Gallery]]|page=5}}</ref> He was born in [[Canterbury]] in 1781<ref name="Harleian" /> as the second son of [[Jacob Schnebbelie]], a [[Confectionery|confectioner]] who later became a noted antiquarian draughtsman employed by the [[Society of Antiquaries of London]].<ref name="Nichols" />
When Jacob died at the age of only 31, leaving his family in poverty, Robert took up his father's profession and continued his work drawing old buildings in London.<ref>{{cite book|title=Landscapes of Retrospection: The Magoon Collection of British Drawings and Prints, 1739-1860|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cnzqAAAAMAAJ|year=1999|publisher=[[Frances Lehman Loeb Art Center]], [[Vassar College]]|isbn=978-0-9644263-3-7|page=52}}</ref> He displayed artistic talent from an early age; in 1795 his mother Caroline wrote to [[John Bowyer Nichols]], one of the editors of the ''[[Gentleman's Magazine]]'' and a benefactor of the family following Jacob's untimely death, to say that she was "taking the liberty of sending you my son, Robert with a few Sketches of his own performance for your inspection". She asked Nichols to consider employing her son "if you think him Capable of copying any little matter for the Mag[azine]".<ref name="MyersHarris2002">{{cite book|last1=Myers|first1=Robin|last2=Harris|first2=Michael|last3=Mandelbrote|first3=Giles|title=Lives in print: biography and the book trade from the Middle Ages to the 21st century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ybMVAQAAIAAJ|year=2002|publisher=[[Oak Knoll Books and Press|Oak Knoll Press]]|isbn=978-0-7123-4796-9|page=135}}</ref>
The adult Schnebbelie occasionally exhibited works at the [[Royal Academy of Arts]] between 1803 and 1821. Engravings based on his drawings were widely published; he made the drawings for many of the plates in [[Robert Wilkinson (cartographer)|Robert Wilkinson]]'s ''Londina Illustrata'' (1808–1825), David Hughson's ''Description of London'' and the ''Gentleman's Magazine'', among others.<ref name=DNB00>{{cite DNB|wstitle =Schnebbelie, Jacob|first =Freeman Marius |last = O'Donoghue |volume = 49|quote=''sources:'' [''Gent. Mag.'' 1792, i. 189; Nichols's ''Lit. Anecdotes'', vol. vi. passim; ''Antiquaries' Museum'', 1800; Redgrave's ''Dict. of Artists''.]}}</ref>
Schnebbelie was described posthumously by John Bowyer Nichols as being "of rather weak intellect, and very capricious in the employment of his time." The death of his mother was said to have affected him to the point that he was "scarcely able to take care of himself."<ref name="Nichols" /> He died in a state of acute poverty in [[Camden Town]] in 1847.<ref name="MoL" /> Nichols wrote that "to the horror of his few friends, his body was found in a lodging, almost destitute of furniture, after having been some days dead; and it was too evident that his death was hastened by privation."<ref name="Nichols">{{cite book|title=Illustrations of the Literary History of the Eighteenth Century: Consisting of Authentic Memoirs and Original Letters of Eminent Persons; and Intended as a Sequel to the Literary Anecdotes |volume=VIII|last=Nichols|first=John Bowyer|authorlink=John Bowyer Nichols|publisher=J.B. Nichols & Son|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JXettTn8UXoC|year=1858|page=551}}</ref> According to [[Samuel Redgrave]], Schnebbelie died of starvation.<ref name="Redgrave1874">{{cite book|last=Redgrave|first=Samuel|title=A Dictionary of Artists of the English School: Painters, Sculptors, Architects, Engravers and Ornamentists|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cJBpAAAAcAAJ|year=1874|publisher=[[Longmans, Green and Company]]|page=363}}</ref>
Views of Schnebbelie's artistic merit vary; he has been described by the Canadian art historian [[Robert R. Wark]] as "gifted",<ref name="Wark1993">{{cite journal|last1=Wark|first1=Robert R.|title=The Gentle Pastime of Extra-Illustrating Books|journal=[[Huntington Library Quarterly]]|volume=56|issue=2|year=1993|page=159|issn=0018-7895|doi=10.2307/3817591|jstor=3817591}}</ref> and by Redgrave as "a good draftsman{{sic}}",<ref name="Redgrave1874" /> though Martin Hardie is less generous, describing both Schnebbelies as "painstaking but niggling in their draughtsmanship" and their work as "not often ris[ing] above a level of good hack work."<ref name="Hardie1966">{{cite book|last=Hardie|first=Martin|title=Water-colour Painting in Britain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wdbqAAAAMAAJ|year=1966|publisher=[[B T Batsford]]|page=xxx}}</ref> A number of his works are on display as part of the collections of the [[Museum of London]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collections.museumoflondon.org.uk/online/object/95096.html|title=Whitechapel School|publisher=Museum of London|accessdate=10 December 2016}}</ref> the [[City of London Corporation]]'s [[Guildhall Art Gallery]]<ref name="Gallery1951" /> and the [[Huntington Museum of Art]],<ref name="Wark1993" /> among other institutions.
